                    <div id="vertical-rules">

                    

	<div id="fb-root"></div>

	<article id="article" itemtype="http://schema.org/NewsArticle">

	<!-- article content here - 2 nested columns for headline and space span 9 and 3. 2 nested below span 9 and 3 for article and secondary sidebar-->
	<!--headline and space-->
	<div class="row-fluid">

		<div id="article-container" class="span9">

			<header>

				<h1 itemprop="headline">Fight Theresa May’s vision of a racist, nationalist Brexit</h1>

				<meta itemprop="description" content="Tory prime minister Theresa May came out for a right wing, racist “Brexit” on Tuesday. May scapegoated migrants for the problems that people face." />

				


			</header>

			

				
	                	by Tomáš Tengely-Evans
				

			

			

		</div><!-- /span9 -->

			<div class="for-print-only">
				<div>
					<time itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2017-01-17">
						Published Tue 17 Jan 2017 
					</time>	
				</div>
				<div>Issue No. 2537</div>
			</div>
	</div>
	<!-- End row-fluid -->
	<!--/headline and space-->

	<!--article and secondary sidebar-->
	<div class="row-fluid">

		<div class="span9 article-content">
			<div id="vertical-rules-content" itemprop="articleBody">

				<hr />

				<div class='image-caption-wrapper'>
<div class='image-holder'><a href='/images1412/Image/2017/2537/theresamay.jpg' rel='prettyPhoto'><img alt='Theresa May' class='article_style1' src='/images1412/Image/2017/2537/theresamay.jpg' /></a></div>

<div class='image-caption'>
<p><span class='caption'>Theresa May (Pic: Number 10)</span></p>

<hr /></div>
</div>

<p>Tory prime minister Theresa May came out for a right wing, racist &ldquo;Brexit&rdquo; on Tuesday.</p>

<p>May scapegoated migrants for the problems that people face.</p>

<p>&ldquo;The sheer volume has put pressure on public services, stretched infrastructure and put downward pressure on wages for working class people,&rdquo; she said&mdash;as if she cares about the lives of working class people.</p>

<p>&ldquo;As home secretary, I saw how you can&rsquo;t curtail immigration numbers as a whole, while there is free movement from the EU.&rdquo;</p>

<p>May added, &ldquo;What I am proposing cannot mean membership of the <a href='https://socialistworker.co.uk/art/43781/The+single+market+is+a+tool+for+the+bosses'>single market</a>.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Since the vote to leave the European Union (EU) last June, the Tories have been torn between bigotry and the demands of big business.</p>

<p>Their friends in the City of London financial district wanted to maintain access to the EU&rsquo;s neoliberal single market.</p>

<p>But the EU&rsquo;s rulers made clear that it would mean keeping the freedom of movement for EU migrants.</p>

<p>The Tories&rsquo; right wing supporters and backbenchers&mdash;and many senior ministers&mdash;see slashing immigration as the main priority.</p>

<p>They are trying to win over Ukip supporters by ramping up racism. May tried to fudge these divisions with the meaningless phrases of &ldquo;Brexit means Brexit&rdquo; and &ldquo;red, white and blue Brexit&rdquo;.</p>

<p>Now, in an attempt to assert control, she has come down hard on the side of slashing immigration.</p>

<p>May&rsquo;s chancellor Philip Hammond fought to keep Britain in the single market.</p>

<p><span class='crosshead'>Abandon</span></p>

<p>Now he has been forced to abandon these hopes&mdash;and is trying to placate big business with promises of giveaways (see below).</p>

<p>But this will not make the divisions within the Tory party disappear or solve the crisis for the ruling class.</p>

<p>May has come out with a clearer position. But time is running out for the Tories&mdash;who are committed to triggering the EU&rsquo;s Article 50 process for leaving the EU in March.</p>

<p>They also face obstacles.</p>

<p>May&rsquo;s talk of making a Britain a &ldquo;global trading nation&rdquo; is steeped in delusion. The Tories will not simply be able to negotiate a free trade deal with the EU and the US.</p>

<p>The Supreme Court is likely to rule that MPs and Lords must approve triggering Article 50 in a parliamentary vote.</p>

<p>Another legal case is being brought forward in an attempt to block Brexit.</p>

<p>The EU&rsquo;s Article 127 suggests there should be a separate process for leaving the European Economic Area, which includes some countries not in the EU.</p>

<p>This could slow the process for leaving the single market.</p>

<p>The danger is that opposition to May and her racism builds around a defence of the neoliberal single market. That&rsquo;s what the Liberal Democrats&mdash;and some in the Labour Party&mdash;hope to do.</p>

<p>We have to seize on Tory weakness to fight for a socialist and anti-racist alternative that says, &ldquo;<a href='https://socialistworker.co.uk/art/43923/No+to+retreat+on+freedom+of+movement'>Yes to freedom of movement</a>, <a href='https://socialistworker.co.uk/art/43959/The+single+market+is+no+solution+for+workers'>no to the single market</a>&rdquo;.</p>

<p>That means building a powerful movement against racism and austerity that can unite our side and take on the Tories and bosses.</p>

<hr />
<div class='image-holder-right'><a href='/images1412/Image/2017/2537/hammond.jpg' rel='prettyPhoto'><img alt='Philip Hammond' class='article_style4' src='/images1412/Image/2017/2537/hammond.jpg' /></a>

<div class='image-caption'>
<p><span class='caption'>Philip Hammond (Pic: UK in Spain)</span></p>

<hr /></div>
</div>

<h2>Hammond&rsquo;s back-up plan is &lsquo;low tax&rsquo; haven for rich</h2>

<p>Chancellor Philip Hammond unveiled the Tory plan for British capitalism if other EU leaders don&rsquo;t accept the Tories&rsquo; Brexit plans.</p>

<p>He pledged to make Britain into a <a href='https://socialistworker.co.uk/art/42530/Private+matters%3A+How+capitalism+hides+its+filthy+hoard'>low tax</a>, low welfare society.</p>

<p>Many EU leaders saw Hammond as an ally in arguing for a &ldquo;soft Brexit&rdquo;, which would keep much of the present set up.</p>

<p>Now that&rsquo;s off the table, they are unlikely to be sympathetic in negotiations.</p>

<p>Hammond is hoping to use the threat of a corporation tax and trade war with the EU as leverage.</p>

<p>He threatened, &ldquo;If Britain were to leave the EU without an agreement on market access, then we could suffer from economic damage at least in the short-term.</p>

<p>&ldquo;In this case, we could be forced to change our economic model.&rdquo;</p>

<p>May echoed Hammond&rsquo;s words in her speech when she said if the EU sought a &ldquo;punitive deal&rdquo; it would be &ldquo;calamitous&rdquo;.</p>

<p>This is part of a desperate attempt to prove to the City of London and big business that the Tories are still on their side despite abandoning the single market.</p>

<p>Top bankers last week resigned themselves to losing their &ldquo;passporting&rdquo; rights, which allows them to trade freely within the EU.</p>

<p>Yet the bosses will demand something in return.</p>

<hr />
<h2>Don&rsquo;t line up with bosses</h2>

<p>The Labour Party and most trade unions responded to Theresa May&rsquo;s speech by attacking her for leaving the single market.</p>

<p>The Labour Party said that the Tories had breached their 2015 manifesto promise to stay in the single market.</p>

<p>Jeremy Corbyn said, &ldquo;I think we need to have a deal that ensures we have access to the market.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We have British jobs dependent on that market.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He added, &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll be putting a case for market access within parliament. We&rsquo;ll be putting a case for regulation of the labour market and all the issues that go with that.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Meanwhile Unite union leader <a href='https://socialistworker.co.uk/art/43912/Migrants+part+of+our+class'>Len McCluskey</a> slammed &ldquo;her determination to appease the hard right in her party and Ukip by talking tough on immigration&rdquo;.</p>

<p>But he also made a dangerous concession to May&rsquo;s racist scapegoating of migrants.</p>

<p>McCluskey said, &ldquo;Real concerns over the freedom of movement can be addressed by sensible labour market safeguards without abandoning the single market.&rdquo;</p>

<p>We need a robust defence of migrants&rsquo; rights and freedom of movement&mdash;without lining up with the bosses and bankers who want to defend the single market.</p>

			</div>
			
			
